Reference-contexts: Phenomenological matter shells (made from incoherent dust, barotropic perfect fluid, or relativistic elastic sheets) have been extensively studied in literature. We found that dust coupled to gravity is an especially handy conceptual tool in interpreting quantum dynamics. <ref> [12] </ref> For spherical dust shells, the advantages of dust appear clearly in the skeleton which remains after spherical minisuperspace reduction. At the phenomenological level, we thus limit ourselves to dust shells. <p> The role of proper time along dust worldlines as a variable which brings the Dirac constraint to the Schrodinger form is quite general and depends neither on symmetry nor on confining the dust to a shell (Brown and Kuchar <ref> [12] </ref>). However, for a spherical shell this role of T is especially transparent and the Hamiltonian constraint automatically appears in the form which is linear in M. That the shell mass should be treated as a dynamical variable becomes clear from the analogy between dust shells and scalar field shells.
